text: Biosynthesis  of  pyranonaphthoquinone  polyketides  reveals diverse  strategies  for  enzymatic  carbon–carbon  bond  formation Mikko  Metsa¨ -Ketela¨ 1,  Terhi  Oja1,  Takaaki  Taguchi2,  Susumu  Okamoto3 and  Koji  Ichinose2 Pyranonaphthoquinones  synthesized  by  Streptomyces bacteria  via  type  II  polyketide  pathways  are  aromatic compounds  build  around  a  common  three-ring  structure,  which is  composed  of  pyran,  quinone  and  benzene  rings.  Over  the years,  actinorhodin  in  particular  has  served  as  a  model compound  for  studying  the  biosynthesis  of  aromatic polyketides,  while  some  of  the  other  metabolites  such  as granaticin,  medermycin,  frenolicin  and  alnumycin  A  have enabled  comparative  studies  that  complement  our understanding  how  these  complex  biological  systems  function and  have  evolved.  In  addition,  despite  the  similarity  of  the aglycone  units,  pyranonaphthoquinones  in  effect  display remarkable  diversity  in  tailoring  reactions,  which  include numerous  enzymatic  carbon–carbon  bond  forming  reactions. This  review  focuses  on  the  current  status  of  molecular  genetic, biochemical  and  structural  investigations  on  this  intriguing family  of  natural  products.

Addresses 1 Department  of  Biochemistry  and  Food  Chemistry,  University  of  Turku, Turku  FIN-20014,  Finland 2 Research  Institute  of  Pharmaceutical  Sciences,  Musashino  University, Shinmachi,  Nishitokyo-shi,  Tokyo  202-8585,  Japan 3 National  Food  Research  Institute,  Kannondai,  Tsukuba-shi,  Ibaraki 305-8642,  Japan Corresponding  author:  Metsa¨ -Ketela¨ ,  Mikko  (mikko.mk@gmail.com) Introduction The  soil-dwelling  bacterial  species  of  the  genus  Strepto- myces  are  well  known  for  their  production  of  a  wide  range of  biologically  active  compounds.  They  are  especially prominent  producers  of  aromatic  type  II  polyketides, which  have  been  utilized  as  antimicrobials  (e.g.  tetra- cycline)  and  anticancer  agents  (e.g.  doxorubicin)  [1]. biosynthesis  greatly  facilitates  rational  design  of  novel compounds  through  various  biotechnological  means. One  distinct  subclass  of  aromatic  polyketides  is  the pyranonaphthoquinones,  which  have  a  fused  three-ring structure  composed  of  a  pyran,  a  quinone  and  a  benzene ring  (Figure  1).  The  p-quinone  is  typically  found  as  the central  ring,  like  in  actinorhodin,  granaticin,  medermycin and  frenolicin,  but  in  the  case  of  alnumycin  A  the  quinone structure  has  an  atypical  position  as  a  lateral  ring  [2–6]. The  remarkable  feature  of  pyranonaphthoquinones  is  the wealth  of  non-canonical  modiﬁcations  made  to  the  core aglycone  units,  which  are  in  many  cases  accomplished  via C–C  bonds.  These  include  the  dimerization  of  two  half- molecules  in  actinorhodin  biosynthesis,  the  dual  attach- ment  of  the  40-keto-D-olivose  deoxysugar  to  the  granaticin aglycone,  the  C-glycosylation  of  medermycin  and  the formation  of  the  unusual  40-hydroxy-50-hydroxymethyl- 20,70-dioxane  unit  in  the  alnumycin  A  pathway.

The  biosynthesis  of  aromatic  polyketides  has  been  exten- sively  reviewed  in  the  past  [1,7]  and  can  be  roughly divided  into  three  sections,  ﬁrstly  the  common  polyketide synthase  (PKS)  pathway  leading  to  the  formation  of  the ﬁrst  polyketide  intermediates,  secondly  the  post-PKS pathway  resulting  in  the  distinct  polyketide  aglycones the  metabolites and  ﬁnally  through  a  range  of  exceedingly  diverse  tailoring  reactions. From  starter  units  to  bicyclic  polyketides The  mechanism  of  formation  of  the  initial  polyketide chain  is  currently  well  understood  with  a  number  of protein  crystal  structures  available  and  the  similarity  of the  system  to  bacterial  fatty  acid  synthesis  (Figure  1).  The actinorhodin  pathway  has  especially  been  investigated  in detail  through  the  pioneering  work  of  Khosla  and  co- workers  [7].  The  key  components  involved  are  a  keto- synthase  (KS),  chain  length  factor  (CLF)  and  acyl  carrier protein  (ACP)  that  catalyze  the  condensation  of  malonyl units  in  a  decarboxylative  manner  into  a  long  polyketide chain  [8–11].  The  CLF  is  homologous  to  the  KS,  but  lacks the  conserved  cysteine  residue  in  the  active  site.

The  malonyl  building  blocks  utilized  in  the  synthesis  are activated  by  the  transfer  from  malonyl-CoA  to  an  ACP, which  is  possibly  catalyzed  by  a  malonyl-CoA:ACP  trans- acylase  (MAT)  [8,12],  although  in  vitro  self-malonylation of  ACPs  has  also  been  demonstrated  [13]. biosynthesis  is  initiated  by  the  decarboxylation  of  mal- onyl-S-ACP,  followed  by  an  interthiol  transfer  of  the formed  acetyl  unit  to  the  conserved  cysteine  residue  of the  KS  (Figure  1).  Decarboxylation  of  the  second  mal- onyl-S-ACP  generates  a  negatively  charged  acetyl  inter- mediate,  which  acts  as  a  nucleophile  and  attacks  the carbonyl  carbon  of  the  ﬁrst  KS-bound  acetyl  unit,  result- ing  in  a  four-carbon  long  diketide  attached  to  the  ACP. The  diketide  is  then  transferred  back  to  the  cysteine residue  of  the  KS,  and  the  next  cycle  is  initiated.  In pyranonaphthoquinone  biosynthesis,  seven  rounds  of chain  elongation  are  conducted  to  generate  octaketides [9,14].  The  KS  and  CLF  share  a  common  thiolase  fold and  form  a  tight  heterodimer  with  a  deep  pocket  at  their interface  into  which  the  growing  polyketide  chain  is extended.  The  depth  of  the  pocket  is  mainly  determined by  residues  in  the  CLF,  which  therefore  is  a  critical component  in  the  determination  of  the  length  of  the polyketide  formed  [9].  Generally  only  one  polyketide of  speciﬁc  length  is  generated,  with  few  exceptions  such as  the  frenolicin  KS-CLF,  which  is  able  to  synthesize both  octaketides  and  nonaketides  [15].

The  alnumycin  and  frenolicin  polyketides  are  primed with  butyryl-S-ACP0 starter  units  synthesized  by  a  dedi- cated  enzyme  system  consisting  of  a  ketoacyl  synthase  III (KSIII),  malonyl-CoA:ACP  transacylase  (MAT0)  and  an additional  ACP  (ACP0),  as  conﬁrmed  through  in  vivo studies  [16,17].  The  homodimeric  KSIII  is  responsible for  a  single  round  of  decarboxylative  condensation  of [18].  The  diketide malonyl-S-ACP0 and  acetyl-CoA  is  subsequently  reduced  by  a  ketoreductase formed  [19]  (KRF),  a  dehydratase  (DHF)  and  an  enoyl  reductase (ERF),  enzymes  possibly  shared  with  fatty  acid  biosyn- thesis  [6],  to  yield  the  butyryl-S-ACP0 starter  unit.  Some- what  surprisingly,  it  has  been  proposed  that  the  MAT0 functions  as  a  proofreading  enzyme,  which  purges  the ACP  of  accidentally  loaded  acetyl  groups  [20].

The  polyketides  formed  are  highly  reactive  and  therefore remain  tethered  to  the  ACPs  to  prevent  aberrant  cycliza- tion  events.  The  instability  of  the  intermediates  has complicated  the  characterization  of  the  polyketide  fold- ing  steps,  and  therefore  both  the  timing  of  dissociation  of the  poly-b-ketoacyl-S-ACP  complex  and  the  exact sequence  of  reactions  have  been  challenging  to  decipher. However,  crystallographic  studies,  especially  by  Tsai  and coworkers,  have  begun  to  shed  light  into  the  cyclization reactions  of  type  II  polyketides.  It  is  believed  that  the  ﬁrst regiospeciﬁc  C7–C12  cyclization  may  already  occur  in  the active  site  of  the  KS-CLF  complex  [9],  which  is  possibly followed  by  C-9  ketoreduction,  aromatization  (ARO/CYC) and  cyclization  of  the  second  ring  (CYC)  before  the  release of  a  bicyclic  intermediate.  The  pyranonaphthoquinone  C-9 ketoreductases  (KRs)  are  NAD(P)H-dependent  enzymes of  the  short  chain  dehydrogenase/reductase  (SDR)  family and  they  have  retained  the  canonical  Rossmann  fold,  as Current  Opinion  in  Chemical  Biology  2013,  17:562–570

conﬁrmed  by  the  structure  determination  of  the  act  KR [21,22].  Recent  biochemical  studies  have  indicated  that  the enzyme  prefers  bicyclic  substrate  analogs,  yielding  support to  the  model  that  the  natural  substrate  is  the  C7–C12 cyclized  ACP-bound  intermediate  [23,24(cid:2)].  Currently,  no structures  are  available  for  ARO/CYC  or  CYC  enzymes from  pyranonaphthoquinone  pathways,  but  the  N-terminal domain  of  the  didomain  ARO/CYC  is  likely  to  be  similar  to the  helix-grip  fold  of  the  monodomain  ARO/CYC  enzymes involved  in  tetracenomycin  [25]  and  R1128  [26(cid:2)]  biosyn- thesis.

Formation  of  the  distinct pyranonaphthoquinone  aglycones The  bicyclic  intermediate  released  from  the  ACP  is  likely to  be  the  point  of  divergence  of  alnumycin  biosynthesis from  the  rest  of  the  pyranonaphthoquinones  (Figure  2).  In the  actinorhodin,  granaticin  and  medermycin  pathways, pyran  ring  formation  is  the  next  biosynthetic  step  [27–29], but  in  alnumycin  biosynthesis  it  has  been  proposed  that hydroxylation  of  the  lateral  ring  precedes  third  ring  cycli- zation  [30(cid:2)].  The  early  timing  of  the  hydroxylation  by  the monooxygenase ﬂavin-dependent  two-component  (FMO)  AlnT  and  the  ﬂavin  reductase  AlnH  may  prevent non-enzymatic  oxidations  in  the  central  ring.  The  third ring  cyclization  of  pyranonaphthoquinones  presents  a remarkable  example  of  divergent  evolution  as  enzymes belonging  to  three  different  families  are  responsible  for the  cyclization  events  [6,31].  While  ActVI-1  and  Med-12, enzymes  of  the  3-hydroxyacyl-CoA  dehydrogenase protein  family,  catalyze  C-3  ketoreduction  leading  to (S)-DNPA  (Figure  2),  the  SDR  enzyme  Gra-6  is  respon- sible  for  (R)-DNPA  (Figure  2)  synthesis.  The  alnumycin pathway  does  not  have  proteins  homologous  to  either  of these  families  and  the  likely  candidate  for  C15  ketore- duction  is  the  oxidoreductase  AlnO  [6].

In  the  actinorho- din  pathway,  subsequent  enoyl  reduction  affording DDHK  has  been  associated  to  the  NAD(P)H  dependent medium-chain  alcohol  dehydrogenase  ActVI-2  (Figure  2) [17].  A  very  unusual  feature  in  actinorhodin  biosynthesis is  the  hydroxylation  at  C-6,  since  both  a  two-component FMO  system  ActVA-5/ActVB  [32]  and  a  cofactor  inde- pendent  ActVA-6  [33]  may  catalyze  quinone  formation [34(cid:2)(cid:2)].  The  non-essential  ActVA-6  belongs  to  a  family  of cofactorless  monooxygenases  with  a  ferredoxin  fold, which  is  able  to  activate  molecular  oxygen  through  util- ization  of  the  substrate  DDHK  [33].  Recent  studies  have conﬁrmed  that  ActVA-5  and  Gra-21  are  in  effect  bifunc- tional  enzymes  responsible  for  the  dual  hydroxylations  at C-6  and  C-8,  whereas  Med-7  and  AlnT  are  monofunc- tional  enzymes  with  different  regioselectivity  [30,35(cid:2)]. Furthermore,  the  ActVA-5/ActVB  system  is  afﬁliated  with an  unusual  moonlighting  epoxidase  activity  in  vitro,  which is  not  required  for  actinorhodin  biosynthesis  [36]. Formation  of  the  dioxane  unit  of  alnumycin  A Recently  the  pathway  responsible  for  the  biosynthesis  of the  dioxane  moiety  of  alnumycin  has  been  elucidated, which  conﬁrmed  that  somewhat  unexpectedly  the  unit  is derived  from  D-ribose-5-phosphate  and  synthesized  in four  distinct  steps  (Figure  3)  [38(cid:2)(cid:2)].  In  the  initial  step, AlnA,  which  is  homologous  to  proteins  from  the  small enzyme  family  of  pseudouridine  glycosidases,  catalyzes the  attachment  of  D-ribose-5-phosphate  to  the  prealnu- mycin  aglycone.  The  overall  C-ribosylation  is  completed by  removal  of  the  phosphate  group  by  AlnB.  Structural and  biochemical  studies  have  suggested  that  formation  of the  C–C  bond  by  AlnA  proceeds  via  a  Michael-type addition,  followed  by  hemi-acetal  formation  and  dehy- dration  [39(cid:2)(cid:2)]. However,  the disparity  in  activities  of  lysine  mutants  of  YeiN  [40(cid:2)(cid:2)]  and AlnA  [40(cid:2)(cid:2)]  alludes  that  the  two  enzymes  may  differ  in their  respective  mechanisms.  The  dephosphorylation catalyzed  by  AlnB  is  likely  to  follow  a  nucleophilic  course in  tandem  with  acid/base  catalysis,  a  fact  well  established for  the  haloacid  dehalogenase  (HAD)  enzyme  superfam- ily  [39(cid:2)(cid:2)]. Deoxysugar  biosynthesis  and  attachment The  biosynthesis  of  the  carbohydrate  units  of  granaticin and  medermycin  are  likely  to  follow  canonical  pathways formation  of  deoxysugars  and  aminosugars for  (Figure  4),  which  have  been  elucidated  by  Liu  and colleagues  in  particular,  and  reviewed  elsewhere  [41]. No  protein  structures  are  available  from  pyranonaphtho- quinone  pathways,  but  several  structures  of  homologous proteins  from  related  antibiotic  biosynthesis  pathways have  recently  been  solved  by  Holden  and  coworkers [42].  The  biosynthesis  is  initiated  by  activation  of  D- is to  dNDP-D-glucose,  which  glucose-1-phosphate  to  dNDP-4-keto-6-deoxy-D-glucose further  converted  by  4,6-dehydratases  as  Gra-17/Med-17, enzymes  of  the  SDR-family.  The  catalysis  involves  a complicated  set  of  proton  transfer  steps  from  and  to the  substrate,  elimination  of  the  C-6  hydroxyl  group, and  hydride  transfer  from  the  substrate  to  NAD+  and

Proposed  deoxysugar  biosynthesis  and  attachment  in  the  medermycin  and  granaticin  pathways.  No  structures  of  the  proteins  involved  in  medermycin and  granaticin  biosynthesis  have  been  solved,  but  structural  studies  have  been  conducted  with  the  following  homologous  enzymes:  the  4,6- dehydratase  DesIV  (bright  green),  1R66  [43];  the  3-aminotransferase  DesI  (light  green),  2PO3  [48];  and  the  aminomethylase  DesVI  (dark  green),  3BXO [50],  which  are  all  involved  in  the  biosynthesis  of  dTDP-desosamine;  the  3-ketoreductase  KijD10  (pale  green),  3RC1  [46],  involved  in  the  biosynthesis  of dTDP-L-digitoxose;  and  the  glycosyltransferases  UrdGT2  (yellow/green),  2P6P  [52],  from  the  urdamycin  pathway.

back.  The  second  step  is  removal  of  the  C-2  hydroxyl group,  which  results  in  the  formation  of  an  unstable  3,4- diketo  intermediate  [44,45].  The  instability  suggests  that the  2,3-dehydratases  Gra-27/Med-16  must  act  in  concert with  the  next  biosynthetic  enzymes  and  in  the  granaticin pathway  the  simultaneous  requirement  for  the  3-ketor- eductase  Gra-26,  which  belongs  to  the  glucose–fructose oxidoreductase  superfamily  [46],  has  been  demonstrated [44].  In  the  medermycin  pathway,  the  reaction  is  coupled to  a  PLP  dependent  transamination  reaction  catalyzed likely  by  Med-20.  The  reaction  mechanism  of most  enzymes  of  the  aspartate  aminotransferase  family  ﬁrst requires  the  conversion  of  PLP  into  PMP  using  glutamate as  the  nitrogen  source,  followed  by  amination  of  the  sugar substrate  [47,48].  The  biosynthesis  of  the  D-angolosamine moiety  of  medermycin  may  be  completed  by  the  action  of the  4-ketoreductase  Med-14  [4]  and  the  SAM-dependent N-dimethylation  by  Med-15,  which  is  homologous  to Pyranonaphthoquinone  biosynthesis  Metsa¨ -Ketela¨ et  al.  567 Current  Opinion  in  Chemical  Biology  2013,  17:562–570 Current Opinion in Chemical Biology classical  methyltransferases  such  as  TylM1  and  DesVI in  the  biosynthesis  of  macrolide  antibiotics involved  [49,50].

The  glycosyltransferase  (GT)  Med-8  is  likely  to  function in  a  manner  similar  to  the  homologous  C–C  bond  forming glycosyltransferase  UrdGT2,  which  catalyzes  the  attach- ment  of  dTDP-D-olivose  in  urdamycin  biosynthesis  [51]. The  mechanism  of  C-glycosylation  by  UrdGT2  has  been suggested  to  resemble  inverting  GTs  and  to  involve  a general  base  responsible  for  the  deprotonation  of  the phenolic  hydroxyl  group  of  the  substrate  [52,53(cid:2)(cid:2)].  The nucleophilic  character  of  the  adjacent  carbon  would  then resonance,  which  would  enable  a increase  nucleophilic  attack  on  the  activated  position  C-10 of the  sugar.  Accordingly,  both  granaticin  and  medermycin are  C-glycosylated  at  an  analogous  o-position,  adjacent  to a  hydroxylated  carbon  of  a  phenol  ring  (Figure  1).  In addition  to  granaticin,  Streptomyces  violaceoruber  produces granaticin  B,  which  is  a  double  glycosylated  granaticin-30- O-L-rhodinoside.  To  reconcile  the  two  glycosylation  steps with  the  presence  of  a  single  GT  (Gra-14),  it  has  been proposed  that  the  ﬁrst  4-ketosugar  attachment  might proceed  in  an  unusual  fashion,  with  the  nucleophilic substitution  of  an  aglycone  with  the  keto-group  of  C- 40,  followed  by  intramolecular  aldol  condensation  [3]. The  4-ketosugar  substrate  was  characterized  as

nucleophilic substitution  of  an  aglycone  with  the  keto-group  of  C- 40,  followed  by  intramolecular  aldol  condensation  [3]. The  4-ketosugar  substrate  was  characterized  as  dTDP-4- keto-2,6-dideoxy-D-glucose,  which  readily  undergoes elimination  of  dTDP  [44].  The  mechanism  of  formation of  the  sugar  attachment  via  C–C  bonds  in  granaticin is biosynthesis  remains  enigmatic  and  further  work  required  in  order  to  comprehend  this  unprecedented sugar  attachment.

Concluding  remarks Over  the  past  decade,  the  majority  of  the  biosynthetic steps  required  for  the  formation  of  pyranonaphthoqui- nones  have  been  elucidated  and  many  individual  reac- level.  The tions  are  understood  at  challenge  for  the  next  decade  will  be  to  understand the  subtle  differences  that  exist  on  the  related  pathways and  how  this  natural  diversity  can  be  utilized  for  the generation  of  novel  natural  products  either  through  use  of the  promiscuity  of  the  native  enzymes  or  by  structure- based  protein  engineering.  The  most  remarkable  feature of  these  metabolites  is  the  highly  conjugated  chromo- phore  system,  which  appears  to  be  well-suited  to  acti- vation  of  molecular  oxygen  as  demonstrated  by  the  non- related  cofactor  independent  oxidoreductases  ActVA-6 [33]  and  Aln6  [38(cid:2)(cid:2)].  The  second  unique  ability  is  the formation  of  various  C–C  bonds  and,  in  effect,  it  would seem  that  the  aglycones  may  be  utilized  both  as  nucleo- philes  (Gra-14/Med-8)  [53(cid:2)(cid:2)]  as  well  as  recipients  of nucleophilic  attacks  (AlnA)  [39(cid:2)(cid:2)]  in  these  reactions. Therefore  from  a  biosynthetic  perspective  the  most  inter- esting  questions  remaining  will  be  the  elucidation  of  the mechanistic  paradigms  for  the  unknown  reactions  leading Current  Opinion  in  Chemical  Biology  2013,  17:562–570

to  C–C  bond  formation  on  the  actinorhodin  and  granaticin pathways.
